		<!-- message -->
		<div><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">
For example, many say that rangers are "broken" our thougt is that they can make it to the high levels and participate in the very high end of EQ just fine, which means, they are not in fact broken.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
No, not broken in the sense that there at any problems which prevent a character from reaching 65, or 70, or whatever level of AA and requesting to join a high end guild and going along on raids.<br />
<br />
However, this does not address the lack of usefulness to said guild. Rangers have little to nothing to offer a raiding guild that can not be done far better than another class. Perhaps if there were no rangers on a raid, one or two warriors would notice they didn't have CoR or maybe a rogue or monk might wonder why they didn't have Pred but honestly, that's about it.<br />
<br />
While this is not broken, I strongly believe it is an exceptionally poor design choice. This is why you hear about "Holy Trinity" classes. This is why you'll see guilds with 10-20 of one class on their roster and 1-2 of another. And you know, those guild are going to continue to recruit more of that 10-20 class and probably figure 1-2 of the other is enough.<br />
This is a fundamental error in EverQuest's design. It created a caste system where one person who spent their time, their money, and their energy to create a level 65, or 70, or whatever character with however many AA points is not even remotly as useful as another player who put in the same effort to create a character which happened to be a "prefered" class.  This to me is a disservice to the player of the "lesser" class. He might be twice as devoted, twice as loyal, and twice as willing to do what he can for a guild than some other guy, but at the end of the day, he's still playing a class that doesn't fit into the world well. This becomes a design issue.<br />
<br />
I would strongly encourage the development team to look into this issue across all classes and work on ways to create an environment where no one class holds such an overwhelming advanage that players of other classes are devalued through no fault of their own other than choosing a class they feel more towards their personality. It is not fair to your customers to allow situations lke this to exist.</div>
