		<!-- message -->
		<div>First of all, thank you for posting here, Brenlo. As Rangers, we all appreciate the feeback, and it's nice to see the Glade get a tip of the hat too. Full disclosure before I get to the issue at hand though: I've been playing one Ranger or another since Kunark and I've followed the progression of the class along the way, but I've never been anywhere near the high-end at any point. So, take my suggestions with an appropriately large grain of salt if you wish.<br />
 <br />
With that in mind, I think it's safe to say that the "meat and potatoes" of what most Rangers want is for our class to be a solid third place on sustained DPS and to be sufficiently tough defensively that we can off-tank effectively against run-of-the-mill mobs and take a few hits from harder mobs without going down right away. Those are the things that would make us consistently useful in a group/raid and thus allow us to avoid the dreaded LFG limbo.<br />
 <br />
When it comes to straight-up Ranger fun, though, it's not the daily xp-grind or even the mass assaults of a raid that do it for me. Personally, I think it's the moments when I can shine <i>as a Ranger,</i> rather than as one of several interchangable DPS machines, that make the game memorable. When I could combine my tracking skill with Harmony and Snare to execute a difficult single-pull; when I can save a caster's hide by grabbing aggro in a split-second or prevent a wipe by off-tanking on a bad pull; when I see a Ranger pop Trueshot and open up a can of you-know-what..... Man, those are the times that I love my class the most. <br />
 <br />
So, in a nutshell, my preferred role/definition for a Ranger is this: a solid DPS/off-tank class with exceptional burst-damage, good outdoor pulling skills and the ability to keep a bad situation from turning into a disaster by grabbing aggro and occupying a mob long enough for the casters to do their thing. In general terms, I think the way to do that is to up our sustained melee DPS (while keeping archery pegged to scale up proportionally), improve mitigation/avoidance, upgrade our Harmony and Snare spell-lines to be effective at higher levels, and build on Trueshot somehow to make that our burst-damage ace in the hole.<br />
 <br />
Anywho, that's just my take on things. Thanks for listening.<br />
 <br />
- RD</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
