		<div><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic"><b>Howdy,</b><br />
 <br />
<b>I did mention that rangers do need some poking and prodding, perhaps some upgrades in some key areas, that does not mean that anything will be taken away. However, if rangers were to receive all of the things they want, we would have to remove other abilities. We cannot allow one class to have everything they want, simply because they want it. We then end up with one class. Where is the fun in that? </b><br />
<b></div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div></b><br />
 <br />
That doesn't seem quite right to me. It's all a matter of degrees. It would, for instance, be rediculous to request, say, a pet, and roughly warrior-ish level damage, and maybe some buffs, and even the ability to slow, as well as having a portion of monklike reflexes and dodging. Except, of course, that it's not, because that's what a beastlord is. It's not the abilities themselves that are overpowered in combination, but rather how much of each we're given.<br />
 <br />
What, precisely, is wrong with being the third/fourth best melee and the fourth best tank, and retaining the utility we have now? What would be wrong with being roughly warrior level melee, using spells to do burst DPS better than that, having the ability to be the fourth best tank, and upping the impact of our utility a bit? Or what would be wrong, to take the other extreme, with doing better than monk damage, tanking worse than monks, and making up the "rest" of the package with the utility we have now?<br />
 <br />
The problem with all of these is how you quantify the "usefulness" of DPS, tanking, and utility. I don't think I'm alone in believing that SOE sees us as having far, far more utility than we really have these days. Especially given the (lack of) upgrades in core lines given to us with the last two expansions.<br />
 <br />
Simply put, our utility boils down to the following these days: Casting spells designed to boost DPS (which still doesn't come close to the DPS classes without these spells) and snare. Snare is not a utility package. I know we have heals, and we have buffs, and we have all sorts of other spells, but the real outcome of all of these is marginal at best, because we fight monsters that can hit for 6+ times the damage a 2 second cast heal does in the same time we cast that heal. We fight mobs that are so vicious and dangerous that it is no service to root them should they get into camp, because that forces them to turn on the nearest person and there's a good chance that the person on the receiving end will die as a result of our attempt to practice crowd "control". We fight mobs that have so few hit points, and such resistances, that we are, quite literally, often better off chasing after a running mob and meleeing it to death before it can get into aggro range of another mob, instead of trying to snare it as it runs away.<br />
 <br />
The game has changed; our utility has not kept up. So now we're (very vocally) asking for this. And as egotistical as it may sound, your experiences as a low level ranger have no bearing here, not because your viewpoint isn't valuable, but because you simply haven't experienced the part of the game where things get horribly mangled with the character with which they get horribly mangled.<br />
 <br />
Yes, you can still be effective in the high end game as a ranger. If you couldn't, your first inclination that there was a problem would have been the mass exodus from the class/game. However, as a member of a team I should be able to pull my own weight, synergizing with my teammates to become a whole that's greater than the sum of its parts. As the game stands now, I synergize with my teammates so that I can pull my own weight. That's a horrible, horrible drain on the team and on the poor rangers who want to be a valuable addition to a group. And it seems to be the point that still isn't getting through. On paper we may be versatile. Realistically, we are not. I say this not because I want to become akin to a rogue, or a monk, or a beastlord, but instead because I miss my ranger greatly, but I can't bring him back without the help of SOE, and at this point I despair of the ability to actually provide the understanding that I have of what the problem actually is.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
