			&nbsp;
			#<a href="showpost.php?s=f4e5389be136e78c8cf535687961a58e&amp;p=617552&amp;postcount=23" target="new"><strong>23</strong></a>
		</td>
	
</tr>
<tr valign="top">
	<td class="alt2" width="175">
			
			<div id="postmenu_617552">
				
				<a class="bigusername" href="member.php?s=f4e5389be136e78c8cf535687961a58e&amp;u=15439">Aluyen</a>
				<script type="text/javascript"> vbmenu_register("postmenu_617552", true); </script>
				
			</div>
			
			<div class="smallfont">Member</div>
			
		
			
			
			<div class="smallfont">
				&nbsp;<br />
				<div>Join Date: May 2001</div>
				<div>Location: Southeast UK</div>
				
				<div>
					Posts: 35
				</div>
				
				<div>   </div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				<img class="inlineimg" src="images/icons/icon1.gif" alt="Default" border="0" />
				
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#333300" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><i>Copying over what I posted on the other thread for sake of completeness:</i><br />
 <br />
I don't believe that Rangers should have to sacrifice ANYTHING for an upgrade! Coming here asking us to choose something to lose is redundant - we are exercising our right as consumers to voice our complaints because we have lost much already.<br />
 <br />
In fact, I don't believe ANY class should have to give something away in order to receive improvements beyond and fixes to a flawed design. That leads to nerfing - something players/customers DESPISE. <br />
 <br />
We are your paying customers, and we pay our subscription fee to have fun, as you point out - it follows that when we stop having fun, we stop paying subscriptions and take our business elsewhere. Shouldn't it be your entire company's driving motivation to make sure that we have as much fun playing EverQuest as possible? <br />
 <br />
I will add more later, but will briefly recap the excellent posts above:<br />
 <br />
Harmony Upgrade (indoor, to allow us to pull effectively in dungeons)<br />
Melee DPS change (below rogue and monk, above warrior)<br />
Defensive upgrades (Dodge &amp; Riposte)<br />
Direct Damage spell upgrade (either in the base damage of the spell, or a Ranger only AA enhancement)<br />
Improved Healing (somewhere below a Paladin, around 800 hp, or a Ranger only AA enhancement)<br />
Improved Buff Lines<br />
Improved Buff Stackability<br />
Group/raid utility<br />
 <br />
Edit: Ok I have some more time to extend my original post. I'll respond to each of your points in turn, and add my own views and opinions as I go.<br />
 <br />
<b>1) Rogue DPS:</b> I don't believe I have ever seen anyone (on the Glade or EQHunter anyway) request that Rangers equal a Rogue's melee damage. I'd be interested to know where you reached the conclusion behind this statement.<br />
 <br />
We don't want to out-damage Rogues, and we don't want to out-tank Warriors, or out-heal Paladins.<br />
 <br />
<b>2) Ranger versatility:</b> I agree with you - I've played a Ranger as a main for 5 years now, and like the druid class that is our parent, we are good at a lot of things. Melee damage, scouting, buffing, healing, archery (in its current form) and tracking - all these things are brought together in the Ranger. We draw the origins of our Damage over Time, Direct Damage and Buff lines from our Druid parent, and over time have been given unique spell lines to give our class flavour. I believe that these spell lines can be expanded upon to give people what they want - however, I also know that you cannot please everyone all of the time.<br />
 <br />
<b>3) Definition:</b> Your comment brings into focus a common problem, one that is partly to blame for the current pro-melee/pro-archery arguments; people are trying to compare themselves to a fictional icon, when that doesn't apply to the EverQquest Ranger. True, those stories draw us into the genre to which this game <br />
belongs, but the specifics are very different.<br />
 <br />
The blame for these arguments also falls with design choices that have been made over the years by the live team, who seemed to change our class focus at times. We have adapted to those choices, and then they were changed again - this makes people feel unsettled, and causes confusion. In addition, some people like one way of doing things, while others prefer the original way - and that is what brought us to the current situation on the EQLive forums. <br />
 <br />
My own definition of my class would be this:<br />
 <br />
The Ranger is the ally of Nature in the same way that the Paladin is a defender of their Faith, and the Shadowknight is allied to the forces of Hatred, Fear and Evil. If you want to include Beastlords in this, they are allied to spiritual forces, including ancestor and animal spirits. Simply put, they are the martial side of their druid parent.<br />
 <br />
Rangers are the defenders of the realm of men, yet prefer to live beyond its borders; they are FAR more comfortable in the wild that in a city. <br />
 <br />
They are the protectors of the weak, who would give their life to save what they have sworn to defend to their last dying breath. When a warrior is focused on absorbing the damage from the attacks of a powerful enemy, the Ranger can act as a "bodyguard" for healers and support classes who may suddenly come under attack by additional foes. When the warrior has the full attention of their enemy, the Ranger can dedicate themselves to doing what they do best - use their blades or bow to lethal effect.<br />
 <br />
A Ranger is the sword of the natural world, who works in harmony with the healing powers of the Druid to adopt the role of "nature's defender". A Ranger wears light (at the heaviest, chain) armor for a balance of protection against the need for great agility and dexterity; whereas plate-clad warriors dominate with large heavy weapons, the Ranger is a graceful, powerful fighter, deadly with their dual blades and mastery of the bow, able to strike from camouflage and fade back into the shadows of the forest with barely a sound.<br />
 <br />
They are able to call upon natural powers to heal himself and his allies and to harm and hinder his enemies. Druids and Rangers possess a superior knowledge of different aspects of the natural realm; the Ranger's will tend towards a more martial way of life. However, even the druid cannot hope to overshadow the Ranger's mastery of survival skills. A Ranger always walks safe in the wild places of the world, blending into outdoor settings almost at will, fading from sight in an instant.<br />
 <br />
Whilst a guardian of the wild places, a Ranger is no stranger to the conflict inherent in nature itself - and has long trained to have the skills to hunt the most dangerous of beasts. Whilst the druid tends to their territories through nurture, the Ranger tends to it by a path "red by tooth and claw", that of natural selection and culling. When an animal goes rabid in a sacred forest, the Ranger is the one that walks inside to put the <br />
ravenous beast out of its misery while others fear to tread in the shadow of the trees.<br />
 <br />
There are aspects of this description that do appear in literary sources, and if you want to see them, PM me, I'm not going to cloud the issue by posting those here. =)<br />
 <br />
Anyway, this my definition of the EverQuest Ranger, the class I love to play - pass that along to the devs and see what they think.<br />
 <br />
<b>4) Melee damage avoidance :</b> since we are a chain class, tanking beneath warrior and paladin remains appropriate. We are not asking for increases to our raw hp or AC, but an increase to Dodge and Riposte would be extremely welcome, and I don't think would step on anyone's toes - just something that allows us to survive long enough to allow a warrior or knight to take the mob's attention back.<br />
 <br />
<b>5) Melee damage output :</b> above a warrior, beneath Rogues and Monks. Maybe some form of melee burst damage AA?<br />
 <br />
<b>6) Healing:</b> should be below a paladin, but definitely above where we are now. I recently had a group in Cazic Thule where I was having trouble patch healing an Enchanter - something is drastically wrong there. We are the hybrid child of the second best healing class in the game. Either increase the base hit points returned for the spells, or give us access to Alternate Advancement lines to make this improvement ourselves.<br />
 <br />
<b>7) Direct Damage spells:</b> either up the base damage caused by these spells, or give us access to Alternate Advancement lines to make this improvement ourselves. Alternatively, lower the cast/recast or mana costs of Ranger specific nukes.<br />
 <br />
<b>8) Harmony upgrade: </b>something that affects mobs all the way to 70, can be used indoors. Either spells that grant these, or Alternate Advancement lines that allow us to tailor our own abilities to these specifications. Pulling has always been a fun part of playing a Ranger, and that has been impacted within recent expansions.<br />
 <br />
<b>9) Buffs: </b>Base attack or base damage bonus buffs, overhaste, stackable Damage Shields or buff increasers. Imbued weapon procs for other classes. A low level pet, or access to part of the Druid charm animal line at higher levels. Something that gives us similar utility in a group or raid comparable to say, a Paladin group heal, or Beastlord mana regen.<br />
 <br />
<b>10) Adjustments: </b>again, I will re-iterate. We as paying customers do NOT need to lose ANYTHING to gain improvements. No class needs to be nerfed to fix a broken part of its own makeup, and no class needs to be nerfed to give improvements to another.<br />
 <br />
Please take the changes we have suggested and USE the Test server; implement suggested improvements there for a decent period of time, get feedback from players and developers to tweak them within reason, look at how the changes alter the difficulty of a particular encounter or affect groups. <br />
 <br />
The best testing your developers can make is to pick a live server, create an adventuring party and level up together. Assign a particular developer or two to each class and get them to gather hands-on information as to how that class operates in a solo, group or raid setting - get them to compile THEIR fun log. If at any point they go "Well, this just sucks!!!" - time to make a change. <br />
 <br />
In closing - no more nerfs, please. And thank you very much for your time.<br />
 <br />
~Aluyen<br />
 <br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
