		<!-- message -->
		<div>Well, when we want abilities akin to other classes we get -<br />
 <br />
<i><b>I think that a rangers strong point is its versatility, that they have much to offer and are not confined to one small role. Yet, I hear from many of you that you would like to sacrifice some of that versatility to gain DPS or defense etc . . . So what would you sacrifice to gain more of something. What is the tradeoff? And that presents the question, are you not losing some of what makes a ranger different by becoming more like another class, say rogues ( which I use as it is the most often used class for comparisons to the DPS rangers would like.) Would that not just make you a rogue? Then why play a ranger? Why not make a rogue in the first place? No, I am not saying that you should all go make rogues, although I am sure some of you will say I did. What I am saying is that the more you struggle to become like another class, the less you are a separate class</b> - Brenlo</i><br />
 <br />
Yet when it is pointed out that many of the abilities that made Rangers speical have been made available to other classes, we get -<br />
 <br />
<b>So you lost it? I do believe you still have it, it is just shared now</b> <i>- Brenlo</i><br />
 <br />
Am I out of line to question why it is ok to share our abilites, yet not be able to share others' abilites with our class?<br />
 <br />
Sorry, I worry when I see such contradictions.<br />
 <br />
 <br />
I agree with this quote, in theory -<br />
 <br />
<b><i>I think that a rangers strong point is its versatility, that they have much to offer and are not confined to one small role</i></b><br />
<br />
The problem with being so versatile, is the fragility of the class balance when Content changes. Content jumps cause much of our utility and versatility to be rendered less than preferable at best, or just flat-out obsolete.<br />
 <br />
Content designers take into account the major factors based on the optimal specialist performing against the content. <br />
 <br />
-Warrior and Knight defense and HPs means Rangers will not be a viable tank. Special defensive abilities (Strikethrough, Stalwart Endurance) mean that Mob's stun rate and defensive skills increase to compensate - Rangers do not recieve these abilities and it hurts - literally.<br />
 <br />
-Rogue and Monk DPS means mob ac and avoidance must be scaled to compensate for these 2 classes, this hurts Rangers.<br />
 <br />
-Caster DPS is such that mobs must be made immune to one or more lines of resists, or at best highly resistant to justify resist debuffs. This cripples Ranger spell DPS via DD.<br />
 <br />
-Kiting classes are discouraged by making mobs immune to root and snare. This takes away a defining ability of the Ranger class. We don't AE snared mobs, yet we can't CC them because other classes can.<br />
 <br />
You see - Content and Class balance have eroded most of what made Rangers special. We've shared our abilities (not by choice), and what have we gained?<br />
 <br />
Any defensive increase to Tank classes, Rangers need to be raised with them. Any DPS increases to melee or casters, Rangers need to be raised along with them. Every class is already ahead of us, we just want to keep pace with the scaling.<br />
 <br />
Most of us don't want to have new abilities. We want our old abilities to work vs endgame content. We want that fun of the lower level versatility to continue to the end. Which at this point, it does not.<br />
 <br />
In my world, I would see Rangers :<br />
1) Doing slighty <b>more</b> <b>melee</b> DPS than a Warrior<br />
2) Doing just <b>below </b>Monk DPS with melee + DD spells<br />
3) Tanking <b>just below </b>Knights capabilities.<br />
4) Healing <b>slightly better </b>than Beastlords<br />
5) Pulling outdoors <b>as well</b> as a Bard or Monk.<br />
 <br />
And for my pet peeves -<br />
<b>Rangers get no Bash.</b> We're listed on many shields, but why would we want to do less DPS than a Knight? We don't get the 1h'ers like they do, and we have no chance to interrupt a Casting NPC. How can we be masters of weilding two 1h weapons, yet not be able to swing a trash can lid?<br />
<b>Selos and Horses and Safe Fall.</b> How is it the masters of the outdoors are the slowest traveling class there is? And we can't run through rough terrain without some kind of Levitation.<br />
 <br />
Some things just don't make sense =p.</div>
