		<!-- message -->
		<div>Originally Posted by <b>Brenlo</b><br />
<i>This was not directed towards you at all Summoon, more to the Rangers that post on the EQ Live boards. They currently are very divided and very vocal and hostile towards each other and my team. While a certain amount of angst is to be expected and even tolerated, some are carrying things to the extreme.<br />
<br />
Now that aside, there are no plans to nerf archery folks. The current plan is to focus on ranger melee. So in the context of melee, what would you like to see added changed, poked and prodded? Please do not say,"We want Rogue DPS" as that is not a reasonable change. </i><br />
<br />
<i><b>To grant you rogue DPS would mean that we would need to take away much of your utility.</b></i><br />
<font color="sienna"><i>Let me start off by saying, I for one, have never asked for Rogue DPS.  I don't think the ranger community as a whole has either.  I visit, and post on the EQ Live boards often, I even sent you a PM (which wasn't reponded to) about the situation there.  We have tried to fit in behind Rogues and Monks in the melee dps category, the place we have been in for many expansions.  It has only been since Potime that the dps disrecpancy has become such a big issue.  The "versatility" we once had has diminishing returns, and our pecking order on the dps scale has had a widening gap between us, and Rogues and Monks.  Your statement, that we would need to have "much of our utility" taken away for rogue DPS makes sense, but you are taking it out of context to what we are asking for.  Am I wrong, in thinking monks are supposed to be about 80% melee dps of rogues, and rangers 60-70% of MELEE dps of rogues?  I don't think we are there, we are maybe 50% or so, making our ''versatility'' not enough to overcome getting a spot in limited-numbers raids and exp groups.</i></font><br />
<i><br />
<b>I think that a rangers strong point is its versatility, that they have much to offer and are not confined to one small role.</b></i><br />
<i><font color="#a0522d">Certainly, our versatility used to bring much to the table.  Our roots &amp; snares landed more often, our harmony line made us viable outdoor pullers, our atk buffs scaled appropriately vs. other hybrid class buffs &amp; our dps was respectable enough should we need to fill the ''dps'' role in a group.  Now however, that is no longer the case.  Our versatility has NOT SCALED with the content, nor has it scaled with the other hybrid classes benefits/skills/etc.  I am not trying to compare rangers to paladins, or beastlords here, but in order for you to claim we have ''versatility as a ranger strong point'' you need to take the overall picture into the whole.  Is our current versatility worth taking us over a Rogue, a Monk, A Paladin, Shadowknight, Beastlord??  The arguement can be made, and from my personal near 300 days of playtime backed up... no, its not.  I feel I play my class very well, and I try to make the most of it.  However, if there is any of the above mentioned classes LFG at the same time as me, I get looked over unless its from my friends.  I do not feel that I handicap my group, but it is starting to have that sensation.  I know, that no matter how much I burn, or how lucky I get on spell resists... my dps isn't matching a rogues, a monks, or even a beast lords.  I also know, that should the tank die, we had better have a wizard in the group to succor, because I cannot tank for much longer than my WS lasts and the first heal lands.  This is big problem.  I have been online 6 hrs a day since OOW came out.  I am currently just shy of lvl 68, while most of the people I see with the same playtime are lvl 70 and AAing... I have had to spend 75% of my time soloing with root and shoot (on mobs that root lasts 3-20 seconds...) ... this is not fun.  You want to talk about the Fun Log... I am not having it.  I struggle to keep up, and I am falling behind to people who I know, if I was playing the same class, I would be well ahead of.</font></i><br />
<i> </i><br />
<i><b>Yet, I hear from many of you that you would like to sacrifice some of that versatility to gain DPS or defense etc . . . So what would you sacrifice to gain more of something. What is the tradeoff?</b> </i><br />
<i><font color="sienna">Once again, you come back to asking us to sacrifice, a tradeoff you call it.  I do not see it this way.  We have had diminishing returns since GoD was released.  I understand we will not be the ranged dps kings that we were in PoP, this was an unintended move by the part of SOE, or perhaps, you were giving us our days of glory for a short while.  We are to focus on melee dps, I for one, can get behind that.  But you need to GIVE US something, not ask us to tradeoff.  We are a warrior &amp; druid hybrid.  You claim we have versatility from this, yet it isn't there.  We have asked, and are continuing to ask, for that versatility to be upgraded to a status quo, instead of falling behind as we see it.  The DPS gain should have been a natural progression to stay in line with the 60-70% of rogue dps, yet it hasn't.  How is asking for this status quo, that we havn't had since GoD asking for the moon?  Where is OUR tradeoff for the drop in DPS?  Where is our increased versatility?  Instead of increased versatility, we have seen no Harmony upgrade, pitiful heal upgrades, and ATK buffs that will NEVER be asked for above the Paladin &amp;/or beastlord lineups.  Once again, I fail to see how you can make this statement, perhaps you can enlighten me with some statistical facts, or personal play experience that leads you to believe we need to give something up here.</font></i><br />
<br />
<i><b>And that presents the question, are you not losing some of what makes a ranger different by becoming more like another class,</b> </i><br />
<i><font color="sienna">I think this question should be more directed at the other classes, that have had versatility given to them that came from our genre.  Lull's to monks (harmony), snares to berserkers, snap-agro abilities, etc.</font></i><br />
<i> </i><br />
<i>say rogues ( which I use as it is the most often used class for comparisons to the DPS rangers would like.) Would that not just make you a rogue? Then why play a ranger? Why not make a rogue in the first place? No, I am not saying that you should all go make rogues, although I am sure some of you will say I did. </i><br />
<br />
<i><b>What I am saying is that the more you struggle to become like another class, the less you are a separate class.</b> </i><br />
<i><font color="sienna">Exactly. We have not received upgrades that distinguish our class.  WE have not received abilities that make us desireable on raids.  If you were a raid leader, and could only take 54 people on a given raid, and it came down to a rogue vs. a ranger, who would you take?  Sure, maybe you are friends with a given ranger, maybe the ranger happens to be lucky enough to sop up every chain drop that has occured and is way better equipped than the random_rogue your looking at... but there is very little a ranger brings to the table in a raid-situation.  Predator line is about it, and the random tank that actually wants to wear Call of the Rathe line.  That is our versatility?  That is our desireability on a raid?  C'mon, please.  We are struggling to find our own definition.  WE don't want to be, or rather, I dont' want to be a rogue clone.  I want to be a ranger, I want to have abilities that a raid would want (Auspice was a good start imo...) I would like to be able to melee for respectable dps with nukes that actually land/increase my dps in bursts rather than decrease it.  I don't see the difficulty in this... (innate triple attack at 60, scaled up to 70... resist mod to nukes... melee disciplines starting at lvl 63...)  I don't believe for one second, that this would push us past monks dps on a sustained level, or even remotely encroach upon the rogues toes.  I don't believe for one second that this would be difficult to implement successfully either.</font></i><br />
<i>The less you are rangers and I am not sure that is what you truly want either.<br />
<br />
So what is it you truly want? Is it to be Legolas or Drizzt Do'Urden?</i><br />
<i><font color="sienna">Why are you even asking this question?  To promote the ''schism'' that you see?  SOE has already stated we are to be the more the Drizzt than the Legolas.  Let's not rehash this argument anymore than it already has been.  Archery can be a viable form of dps, you could even add unique abilities into it.  Put archery dps near where our current melee dps is, boost the melee dps to fall in the 70% realm of rogue dps and you will most likely make both ''camps of the schism'' happy.</font></i><br />
<i>Those are great characters in literature but don't really fit well into an MMO. Everyone has to have a role in an MMO and no one class can be a "superclass", now I do know that everyone thinks that there are superclasses but in the grand scheme of things, there is no one class that is more "Uber" than any other. They may be better at specific things but they have their weaknesses as well. So where do you want rangers to fit in?<br />
<br />
So the problem we face, both you the ranger community and I, the guy who tries to represent your interests here (Yes that is what I do) is defining what you want and what you are willing to lose to gain it. I, personally, think rangers are fine. I think they are fun. </i><br />
<br />
<i><b>No, I have not played a ranger to 65 with hundreds of AAs but I have played one. So now I ask you, do you have fun playing a ranger? If not, why?</b> </i><br />
<i><font color="sienna">This is part of the problem.  Until you sit around LFG, or soloing for most of your EQ experience, I don't see how you can understand the plight, and yes, I call it a plight, of the high-end ranger.  What level did you play a ranger to?  Or what level ranger did you hop on for a brief moment?  I am not having fun, because I am not desired.  I do not feel this is because of how I play my class, but because of the class itself.  Rangers are VIEWED AS DPS.  Does that make sense?  WE are lumped in with wizards, rogues, monks, beastlords  berzerkers, even shadowknights and warriors sometimes as the ''dps slot'' for a group.  There is not enough 'versatility' we have to offer to put us on an equal playing field with the other classes.  Of that mix, Beastlords lately have achieved the ''super class'' status, as their versatility far outstrips ours, and their dps is not sacrificed in the process.  Not trying to make it a this class has that argument, just making a point.</font></i><br />
<br />
<i>Please no responses equating you to another class. No, I don't have fun because I do less DPS or I parse lower than a warrior. </i><br />
<i><font color="sienna">Its simple, I don't fun because I am forced to solo.  I dont' have fun because I sit outside the raid for 3 hours, waiting to be invited right at the end for my flags, because my guild at least has taken pity on me, and allows me to progress with them.  I don't have fun, because my class is considered inferior.</font></i><br />
<br />
<i><b>Parse your fun log (yes I know there is no actual fun log, but there should be) and tell me what makes the ranger class fun and what does not. Once we have determined that, then we can figure out where to poke and prod.</b></i><br />
<i><font color="#a0522d">I will start having fun again when I can find groups.  I will start having fun again, when I am wanted equally amongst other classes on raids.  I will have fun again, when I have AA choices worthwhile to spend my time grinding to get.  I will have fun again, when my spellbook is de-gimpified.  I will have fun again, when I can spot heal a cleric or chanter.  I will have fun again, when someone looks at me and go, wow, that was cool!  I have posted AA ideas, as a result, most of them were given to other classes.  They were focused on melee improvements, nothing overpowering, just flavor for the class.</font><br />
<br />
Thanks folks and thanks for reading this long winded post.</i><br />
 <br />
