				<div style="font-style:italic">I think that a rangers strong point is its versatility, that they have much to offer and are not confined to one small role. Yet, I hear from many of you that you would like to sacrifice some of that versatility to gain DPS or defense etc . . . So what would you sacrifice to gain more of something. What is the tradeoff? And that presents the question, are you not losing some of what makes a ranger different by becoming more like another class, say rogues ( which I use as it is the most often used class for comparisons to the DPS rangers would like.) Would that not just make you a rogue? Then why play a ranger? Why not make a rogue in the first place? No, I am not saying that you should all go make rogues, although I am sure some of you will say I did. What I am saying is that the more you struggle to become like another class, the less you are a separate class. The less you are rangers and I am not sure that is what you truly want either.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
Brenlo, I am not finding ANYWHERE where Rangers are asking to be more like rogues.  In fact, part of the whole melee v. archery thing is because a lot of rangers are afraid that by forcing us to melee, you are the ones trying to make us like rogues.<br />
<br />
Look at the post I quoted just now in the last couple paragraphs.  That post, and many others on the boards, clearly state that rangers DON'T need to do equal DPS to rogues AS LONG AS their utility is re-evaluated to bring them back in line with where they are supposed to theoretically be.  The problem is, right now, neither our DPS <b>nor</b> our utility is where it needs to be in the current game.  Both need to be adjusted upward.  DPS needs to be adjusted upward to 70-80% of a rogues DPS and utility spells needs to be adjusted to be fuctional in the current content.  Those utility spells, when functional, will take the place of that missing 20-30% of DPS.  Do you see what we are saying now?<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">So what is it you truly want? Is it to be Legolas or Drizzt Do'Urden? Those are great characters in literature but don't really fit well into an MMO. Everyone has to have a role in an MMO and no one class can be a "superclass", now I do know that everyone thinks that there are superclasses but in the grand scheme of things, there is no one class that is more "Uber" than any other. They may be better at specific things but they have their weaknesses as well. </div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
I notice you left the last three letters off that abbreviation.  Isn't the term actually MMO<b>RPG</b>?<br />
<br />
Once again allow me to direct your attention back to a post on your very own boards:<br />
<a href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=rangerbalance&amp;message.id=11874#M11874" target="_blank">http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq...id=11874#M11874</a><br />
<i>"Archery rangers" are NOT asking to exceed melee.  Very few, in fact, are asking to equal melee.  What we want is a choice.  A choice to make our character be who we want our character to be.  Let's not forget that MMORPG stands for--massively multiplayer online ROLE PLAYING GAME.<br />
<br />
Let me back up and emphasize that again: ROLE PLAYING GAME<br />
<br />
Now, I've done a lot of role-playing in my life.  I've done dice games and non-dice games.  I've done some really hard-core character-centric make-believe roleplaying.  The point of a ROLE PLAYING GAME is to create a character, a unique character that conveys something YOU want to pretend to be for a while, and to make it so, if just for a while.  This means that SOE needs to be offering us MORE choices to customize our characters, not LESS.  Otherwise, it just becomes a first-person shooter game.  If I wanted to play an FPS, I wouldn't have started to play EQ.  I started to play EQ because I understood it was an RPG, not an FPS.<br />
<br />
So, the fact that SOE is actually taking an option for a viable character path AWAY from us is a disturbing one.  It shows that EQ is trending away from the customizability of role-playing toward cookie-cutter toons such as are found in FPS.  That's not what I signed on for.<br />
<br />
So, back to the point I was trying to make.  Your statement of what you think "archery rangers" are asking for is incorrect.  We don't want superiority.  We want viability and flexibility.  We want to be able to customize our character in such a way as to make it "different but equal."  That means trade-offs.  Most of us are prepared to accept those.  We do a certain percentage less damage in exchange for a certain amount of decreased inherent risk.  Fine.  No problem.</i><br />
<br />
I know everyone is invested in the terms "class balanace" and "class definition" and  "class role" but I would advise SOE to scrap those terms and assimilate a couple new ones in their stead: Class Proportion instead of "class balance/definition" and Character Paths instead of "roles."<br />
<br />
<b>CLASS PROPORTION</b>:<br />
There are 6 factors that determine a class's desirability in raid/group situations.  Those factors are:<br />
<br />
Tanking<br />
Healing<br />
Crowd Control<br />
Buffing/Debuffing<br />
DPS<br />
Misc. Utility (corpse runs, scouting, pulling, etc.)<br />
<br />
Each of these needs to fall on a certain scale.  The further certain ones are to one end, the further others should be to the other end.  Ideally, each class should have two of these abilities at the maximum end, two at the minimum end, and two somewhere in the middle.  That would make the characters well rounded.<br />
<br />
So, for example, here's what the tanking scale should look like. (this is just to give an example, not a complete set up the way it should be.)<br />
<br />
1=Warriors<br />
2=Shadow Knights<br />
3=Paladins<br />
4=Rangers<br />
5=silk classes<br />
6= zerkers?<br />
7= rogues/bsts/monks<br />
<br />
0| -<b>5</b>-------------------<b>7</b>------------<i>6?</i>---<b>4</b>--------<b>3</b>---<b>2</b>----<b>1</b> |100<br />
<br />
(Incidentally, there are 50 "ticks" on this scale, so each space is about 2%, so another way to look at it is)<br />
<br />
Warriors= 100% tanking ability<br />
SKs=92% tanking ability<br />
Pallies = 86% tanking ability<br />
Rangers = 70% tanking ability<br />
silk classes = 2% tanking ability (taking rune, etc, into consideration, otherwise should be 0)<br />
Zerkers = 62% tanking ability (assuming since they don't have a taunt skill, they aren't supposed to exceed rangers.)<br />
Other DPS classes = 40% tanking ability<br />
<br />
Now let's take a look at healing:<br />
1=Cleric<br />
2=druid<br />
3=shaman<br />
4=paladin (cleric hybrid)<br />
5=ranger (druid hybrid)<br />
6=beastlord (shaman hybrid)<br />
<br />
0|---------------------------<b>6</b>----<b>5</b>---<b>4</b>------<b>3</b>-----<b>2</b>-----<b>1</b>|100<br />
<br />
Where did I pull these numbers from? Well, let's say a cleric is 100% healer.  A druid is 90% of a cleric insofar as healing goes, and a shaman is 80%.  Those numbers are pretty arbitrary, again, this is more for example than precision.  But now, let's say a paladin, the cleric hybrid, is 70% of a cleric's healing...this means a ranger should be 70% of a druids healing (70% of 90 = 63%) and a beastlord should be 70% of a shaman's healing (70% of 80 = 56%).<br />
<br />
<br />
So, as you can see, each class falls somewhere IN PROPORTION to the rest of the classes in this 6 major functions.<br />
<br />
So here are all 6 scales and where I feel Rangers should fall on each of them.<br />
<br />
TANKING<br />
0|-----------------------------------X---------------|100  -- Ranger = 70%<br />
(warrior represents 100, all others need to fall in proportion to that)<br />
<br />
HEALING<br />
0|-------------------------------X-------------------|100 -- Ranger = 63%<br />
(Cleric represents 100, all others need to fall in proportion to that)<br />
<br />
CROWD CONTROL<br />
0|-----------X---------------------------------------|100 -- Ranger = 20%<br />
(enchanter represents 100, all others need to fall in proportion to that)<br />
<br />
BUFFING/DEBUFFING<br />
0|-----X---------------------------------------------|100 -- Ranger = 10%<br />
(Shaman represents 100, all others need to fall in proportion to that)<br />
<br />
DPS<br />
0|---------------------------------------X-----------|100 -- Ranger = 80%<br />
(rogue represented 100, all others need to fall in proportion to that)<br />
<br />
MISC. UTILITY<br />
0|--------------------------------------------------X|100 -- Ranger = 100%<br />
(well, frankly, RANGERS should represent 100 here.)<br />
<br />
Now, let's do the math.  (70 + 63 + 20 + 10 + 80 + 100)/600 = 57.17%<br />
<br />
Wow!  Look at that.  In the end, we fall right smack dab in the middle(50%, +/- 7), which is exactly where we SHOULD fall, and where ALL classes should fall.  These numbers actually appear to be a little top-heavy, likely as a result of the fact that the healing assumptions are so arbitrary, those should probably be tweaked down quite a bit, and crowd control needs to be tweaked UP quite a bit.  But the point is, when speaking of trade-offs, fine, we're down with that.  We give up aptitude in the ability to buff and debuff for the ability to do better DPS, etc.  <br />
<br />
In the end, looking at it this way means that defining a classes niche in the game is quite simple.  Simply figure out where they are SUPPOSED fall on each of those 6 scales, then take a look at their current skillset to see if, in practice, they do indeed fall there.  If not, tweak as needed.<br />
<br />
<b>CHARACTER PATHS</b><br />
The term "role" is a rather rigid one.  It pretty much implies that there is little to no room for player customization in the function their toon is supposed to fulfill.  Seeing as this is, indeed, a role-playing game, you need more flexability, not less.  I direct your attention to the following post:<br />
<a href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Rangers&amp;message.id=4266#M4266" target="_blank">http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq...e.id=4266#M4266</a><br />
<br />
What you need to do is incorporate some of the branching class structure idea from EQ2 into EQ.  Allow people to choose what they want to be good at, and attach to each field of excellence a reciprocal are of insufficiency.  Therefore, people have the CHOICE as to what they can be and can't be, and the tradeoffs they are forced to make, they make of their own choosing.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
