Ok, I'll play this game.  Here's my fun log for the last few weeks.  I will rate my "fun factor" on a 5-star scale.<br />
<br />
September 2, 2004:<br />
Raided Cornaiv in PoWater.  Raid was mostly a lot of v. tedious "hurry up and wait" logistical stuff, as most raids tend to be, but once we got ready to engage Corny, the fun began.  I got to be on the snare/root team that kept the mini-named busy while the rest of the raid dealt with the waves of spawn prior to the corny fight itself.  We did a good job, made it through all the spawn waves and the 3 mini-named, and got Corny down to 90% before we wiped.  Being on the snare/root team, I felt useful and needed even though I wasn't actually fighting.  All in all, a fun raid.<br />
Fun Factor Rating: *****<br />
<br />
September 9, 2004:<br />
Raided The Rathe Council for the first time.  After v. boring logistical nonsense was done, the fun began.  We got through all 6 of the mezzable mobs and were on the third non-mezzable mob before we wiped.  That's a first on our server, no one else ever got past the second mezzable mob on their first attempt.  V. cool.  I was assigned the responsibility of keeping the mezzed mob from regenning in the event it got mem-blurred my the mez, by boxing it without weapons to keep some agro going.  Extremely boring, though necessary, job, and can't get past the suspicion that the reason I was assigned this task is because my DPS and utility is so sub-par that I was of more use doing zero DPS and simply swinging harmlessly at the mob for hours on end.<br />
Fun Factor: **<br />
<br />
September 13, 2004:<br />
Raided The Rathe Council again, last raid before OOW goes live.  Guild leader has declared no raids for the next week to give members a chance to level up to 70 before we resume raiding.  Same job as last time, same suspicion that the reason I got is is because I really wasn't able to contribute much otherwise.<br />
Fun Factor: *<br />
<br />
September 15, 2004:<br />
OOW went live yesterday.  Don't have OOW, therefore am immune to all the furor.  Hope to use this week to gain AAs.  Time spent LFG: 4 hours.  Time spent in groups: 1.5 hours.<br />
Fun factor: *<br />
<br />
September 16, 2004:<br />
Hours spent LFG: 5.  Attempted to solo in GoD.  Times killed: 3.  Mobs killed: 0.<br />
Fun Factor: *<br />
<br />
September 17, 2004:<br />
Spent time doing some tradeskill stuff while looking for a group.  Hours spent LFG: 6.<br />
Fun Factor: *<br />
<br />
September 19, 2004:<br />
Hours spent LFG: 3.  Hour spent in a group: 1.5 (a single hard LDoN that ended in a success, yet a wipe.)<br />
Fun Factor: ***<br />
<br />
September 20, 2004:<br />
Hours spent tradeskilling because I've given up attempting to look for a group: 4<br />
Fun factor: **<br />
<br />
Average fun factor from 9/2/04-9/20/04: **<br />
<br />
Ok, so there is my fun parse, by your request, Brenlo.  When I have a clearly defined role that makes me uniquely useful to my group and/or raid, I have a blast.  When I spend hours upon hours LFG because no one wants me because my DPS is sub-par and my utility, while it looks great on paper, doesn't live up to its potential because it simply doesn't work the way it should, I don't have any fun at all.  When I am shuffled off into boring and monotonous roles because I don't contribute enough in other areas for those same reason, again, don't have a lot of fun.<br />
<br />
So, I don't fail to have fun because of where I stack up against other classes.  I fail to have fun because I can't get a group.  Because NO ONE NEEDS ME.  There is nothing I can do that other classes cannot do as well or better.  THAT is why my DPS needs to be increased, and why my utility needs to be tweaked to be viable in current content.  So that I don't have to spend all my time LFG and can get back to having fun.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
