		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
We aren't asking for (many) new things.  For the most part, we are asking for what we are theoretically supposed to be able to do to work the way it's supposed to work.<br />
<br />
Rangers look great on paper, but in reality, they just don't live up to their potential.  About 75% of that problem could be taken care of by doing the following, very easy things:<br />
<br />
1) upgrade harmony.  We can't pull if we can't harmo the mobs.  There's absolutely no reason why we should have been bypassed for this spell in OOW, and no reason for the statement made in the very first response to the ranger Top 10 list, which was that there are no plans to improve Harmony for rangers.  Rangers have a pretty clear role with their previous Harmony spell as pullers, and by not upgrading Harmony, you ARE taking that role away from us, by omission-nerfing it.<br />
<br />
2) Give us resist modifications on our snare and root spells, and some increased ability to manage agro, including a higher taunt cap, and re-evaluated agro-rates for our snares and DoTs.  Peel-And-Park crowd control is an accepted method of dealing with multiple mobs, and rangers have the tools to do it, in theory.  The problem is, those tools don't work as well as they should in the current content.  So fix them and let us have that role back.<br />
<br />
3) Give us something to use our mana on.  There is no reason for the recast time on our nukes to be so long that we are back to full mana before we are able to cast them again.  Frankly, I would prefer my mana to go toward healing or something other than DPS.  I can melee or use my bow if I want to do DPS, I don't need nukes or DoTs, except to grab agro.  So give me some heals that will help me help my groups.<br />
<br />
4) Give us DPS that puts us in a proper place in proportion to other offensive DPS classes.  There is no reason why our DPS should BARELY exceed that of a warrior, who with his ability to tank has tons more appeal for groups than we do.  Again, 70-80% of a Rogue's DPS is where we should fall out.<br />
<br />
See...we're not asking for anything new.  We're not asking to be uber.  We're just asking for our theoretical potential to be made into actual potential.  We're asking you to take what looks great on paper and make it a reality.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">So, would an increase to melee dpw make the game more fun for you? Perhaps some discs or AAs related to dps output? Some of what I see suggests that it would help. Let's hear some more on that point please.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
Again, it's a two-pronged problem.  Yes, a DPS boost is definitely needed, and I highly encourage you to implement it via disciplines and skills, not AAs.  We shouldn't have to buy AAs in order to fall in proportion to where we need to be.  A ranger with 10 AAs should be in proportion to other classes with 10 AAs.  A ranger with 500 AAs should be in proportion to other classes with 500 AAs.  If you make our ability to do proportionate DPS AA-dependent, then it ceases to become proportionate, because our COST is disproportionate.  A ranger with 50 AAs should do 80% of the melee damage of a rogue with 50 AAs.  A ranger should NOT have to have 200 AAs to do 80% of the damage of a rogue with 50 AAs, and that is currently the way things stand.<br />
<br />
It's not a matter of "balance" so much as it is one of "proportion."  Bring us into PROPORTION with the other offensive-DPS classes.  Then take our spells and make them work the way they are supposed to, because I assure you, right now, they DO NOT.<br />
<br />
Re: Harmony and nuking:<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">So you lost it? I do believe you still have it, it is just shared now.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
We don't mind SHARING it.  The problem is that these other classes now EXCEED us, where they were equal or inferior in regards to those particular skills before.  By making them better than us at something we used to be able to do, you ARE taking it away from us, because why would anyone want us for it when they can have someone else who can now do it better?  Do you see?<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Now, I did try to start a discussion on definition. I posted that we were now going to focus on melee as part of the ranger definition and knowing that, where would you like to see the class go. <br />
<br />
I was met with this kind of response. You also misunderstand my role, I do not write class definitions, I do not make changes to your class. I pass along concerns, concerns that are well thought out and well written. I pass along any responses I get to the community. Depending on how things are going, responses and changes can take time. There is nothing I can do about that. It is an unfortunate aspect of our busy schedules. Most days, I do not even get to post much, and I apologize for that as well. We have lots going on and the fact that you may not hear from me or a member of my team does not mean we are ignoring you or have lost interest, simply that we are busy. <br />
<br />
Today I had some open time, so I am spending it here in an attempt to get some good dialogue going. Some folks are contributing to that, and I thank you. Let's continue it as I may not have time to post here tomorrow or even again until next week. But that does not mean that you cannot talk about it, discuss it and share your ideas on where you think your class should be.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
I would caution you, Brenlo...you've started the ball rolling here, and now you have to keep it rolling, or else it's simply going to become EQLive, mark 2.0.<br />
<br />
As I edit this post the morning after I initially made it, I am going into my 6th hour working on this post.  There are some other very long posts here as well, posts which obviously required a great deal of effort to write.  When people put that much of themselves into an endeavor, they don't like to see their efforts go unacknowledged.  If you want to use this forum to harvest your input for the developers, great...but you need to understand that these people are working bloody hard on these posts and they need something more than a blanket "that has been passed along (and promptly never mentioned again)" or things will get unpleasant once more.<br />
<br />
Also, we KNOW that SOE makes hundreds of thousands of dollars a month off our subscription fees.  Maybe they ought to consider hiring more customer service people if you and Ashlanne and Ky can't take the time to respond when the customers beg you to do so.<br />
<br />
Re: The Top-10 list:<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">We get to those as we can and again, not everything you ask for is going to be changed. We will be honest as to when something will not be changed and all we ask is that you be reasonable in your response.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
Fair enough.  But in return, you need to be reasonable in your refusals.  Refusing to upgrade harmony to bring it to level 70 was NOT reasonable.  It's simply inexcusable.<br />
<br />
Also, no reasonable explanation was given for many of the refusals, such as refusing auto-ranged attack for rangers yet saying you would consider auto-twist for bards.  "It would be too powerful" is NOT a reasonable answer, not without further explanation.  How would it be too powerful?  How very powerful can it possibly be to justify letting your paying customers sustain real-life injuries rather than fix it?  Take me down that slippery-slope, please.<br />
<br />
Believe it or not...we are perfectly willing to be reasonable.  But we would like to see a little reasonability from your end first.  Some of the refusals on the Top 10 list were NOT reasonable.<br />
<br />
<br />
Re Archery DPS:<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Point one, Archery DPS is pretty much risk free. There is virtually no danger to the archer. Melee DPS on the other hand is not. So DPS is not DPS. To have a class that can do rogue damage and generate no agro from a distance is not a good thing for the game. That is what we would have if we were to continue to boost archery DPS.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
Brenlo: This claim that archery DPS is risk-free is simply untrue.  It's no more risk free than sending in your pet, or nuking, or DoT'ing.  We can't get out of the mobs AoE range, most mobs even in Tier 3 PoP have AoE ranges that exceed that of archery.  At the same time, even though we aren't out of mob AoE range, we are out of the range of AoE heals...so we are taking hits but unable to be healed.<br />
<br />
Yes, we don't take DS, riposte, or rampage damage, but guess what?  Neither do pet classes, DoT classes, or nuke classes.  Does this mean that you are going to take beastlord/mage/necro pets away?  Are you going to tell wizards to stop nuking and get in there and start meleeing?<br />
<br />
Yeah, I didn't think so.<br />
<br />
<b>Well, those classes carry more agro potential than archery...</b><br />
<br />
Ok, fine.  Reasonable point.  So increase archery agro to be similar to that generated by other ranged-damage classes, like wizards and necros.  If we get summoned, we will know we overdid it, just like they do.  Part of the skillset that separates a really good wizard or necro is knowing how much damage they can do without generating too much agro.  Make archery the same way.<br />
<br />
<b>...and they use mana to do their damage, while archery uses none.</b><br />
<br />
Ok, again, another reasonable point.  But several people have said already, "Tie archery to the endurance bar" so that it's not "free" damage.  I direct you to the following posts:<br />
<a href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=rangerbalance&amp;message.id=7286#M7286" target="_blank">http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq...e.id=7286#M7286</a><br />
<a href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=rangerbalance&amp;message.id=11826#M11826" target="_blank">http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq...id=11826#M11826</a><br />
<br />
There are many other posts which recommend essentiall the same thing.  Make optimal archery damage have a mana or yellow-mana "cost" so that it can't be considered "free" DPS.  But at this point, I've been working on this post for over 3 hours, so I'm not going to dig them all up.<br />
<br />
Digest version:<br />
<b>Ranger melee</b> = 70-80% rogue melee<br />
<b>Ranger archery "free" archery damage </b>(i.e. doesn't cost mana or yellow-mana) = 85-90% of ranger melee damage, which is, in turn, 70-80% of rogue melee DPS.  The reason archery should only be 85-90% (some may even be willing to go as low as 80%) is because of the DECREASE in inherent risk (notice I don't say lack of inherent risk.  There IS risk, especially from the monster AoE spells mobs are casting these days.)  <br />
<b>Ranger Archery damage that has a cost </b>(mana or yellow-mana) = 90-95% ranger melee DPS for long-term sustained DPS, and exceed melee DPS for short-term burst DPS (special 30-second disciplines, etc.)<br />
<br />
Basically, both archery and melee DPS needs to go back and be retro-tweaked to keep these proportions consistent throughout a ranger's lifespan (<a href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=rangerbalance&amp;message.id=11882" target="_blank">http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq...essage.id=11882</a>)<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Point Two, we do have ideas and thoughts and stuff is already in the works (no I cannot tell you yet) but does that mean we should not talk to you about it? Would you rather we just made changes? Isn't that what got us here? </div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
I'm not understanding what you are asking here Brenlo.  You HAVEN'T been talking to us about it.  You have been making the occasional decree from On High, but there has been little-to-no actually dialogue involved.<br />
<br />
So, by all means, TALK to us.  Tell us as much as you possibly can about what's in the works.  COMMUNICATE with us.  If you do that, SO VERY MANY of the problems existing on the EQLive boards and elsewhere will just melt away.  Just do it.  Give us as much detail as you possibly can, then actually LISTEN to what we have to say in return.  That is what you have been failing to do in recent months.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">A big part of the communication issues we are all having, and I have discussed this with the class correspondents at length, is we speak a different language. Broken to you means something entirely different than it does to us. When we read, Spell X is broken because it does not do enough damage, what we might hear is, Spell X does not work the way I want it to, thus I feel it sucks. Had that been presented as, spell X does less damage based on the mana to damage ratio that our other class spells have, well now that is a whole different story and something that our designers can actually look at and measure. It is often hard to measure how much you feel something "Sucks", as I am sure you can imagine.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
Ok, I can see how this might be a problem, but you are omitting mention of the various posts which go into deep and very conherent detail on WHY something is not working, rather that just saying, "it sucks."  Example, the following thread:<br />
<a href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=rangerbalance&amp;message.id=5980#M5980" target="_blank">http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq...e.id=5980#M5980</a><br />
<br />
This is a very complete list of what people feel is "broken" for rangers, and was generally agreed upon by both sides of a melee/archery debate.  At no point does it say something "sucks."  It gives very deep detail.  So you can't say that there have been no attempts to communicate what isn't working, or that all of them have been mishandled in translation.<br />
<br />
Meanwhile, consider that the "lost in translation" aspect of communication between SOE and its customers happens the other way as well.  When you say <i>"dual-wielding for all enounters"</i> followed by <i>"no archery upgrades"</i> people hear <i>"you aren't supposed to be using your bow at all, so we are taking it away from you by making it inadequate"</i>.  As was stated earlier, had that "all encounters" statement been made more sensitively and diplomatically, things would NEVER have gotten to the point they did.  Imprecise communication goes both ways.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">I will not post ratios as I think those do everyone a disservice, but there is talk of boosts to ranger, melee DPS. We do feel that currently rangers are a little farher behind than we would like them to be and talks are ongoing on how best to fix that. <br />
<br />
Archery will not be changed but neither will it receive any significant boosts in the near future. It will be in a holding pattern.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
Brenlo, I think ratios are necessary.  Or at the very least, an explanation of how they can possibly be harmful is required.  How do they do everyone a disservice?  What is so very wrong with wanting to understand where we are supposed to fall in the great scheme of things?  By refusing to give precise information and using a vague excuse to do so, you convey the impression that you don't actually HAVE any precise information, and that the refusal is just a smokescreen to cover up that fact.<br />
<br />
The fact is, right now, a lot of people think that SOE doesn't have a clue.  So prove us wrong.  Show us you do.  Give us and much precise and detailed information as possible to prove that serious thought IS going into these issues.<br />
<br />
All classes need to fall someplace on a scale...it's our only way to gauge our viability.  And revisiting the communication issue, "holding pattern" sounds an awful lot like what some people on the EQLive boards call "omission nerf."<br />
<br />
Let's be specific here.  Vague statements of things being "in the works" simply aren't good enough.  The reason the recent "bard nerf" has gone off so smoothely is because Grumbuk was in communication with the bards, telling them what to expect and asking them for their input.  We need to do the same.  If lack of communication and lack of understanding where each end of the issue was coming from is what got us to this place (and I firmly believe it is) then we need CLEAR, CONCISE statements of what we can expect, so that we can work from there.<br />
<br />
With that in mind, here are my questions:<br />
<br />
What is the melee DPS scale, and where do Rangers fall into it?  What is the DPS heirarchy and what is being done to insure we are in our proper place within it?<br />
<br />
Taking the premise that the lack of archery upgrades is a temporary issue, to allow melee DPS to increase to be where it should be in proportion to to archery DPS, where does it end?  At what point does archery stop being in a "holding pattern."  People seem attached to the 85-90% figure.  Some are willing to go as low as 80%.  What is the optimal proportion between archery and melee DPS?  What is being done to make sure things fall in there and remain there.<br />
<br />
No more shadow-dancing here.  We need concrete answers, not dodges and vague half-answers.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Brenlo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">I am pretty sure Harmony was not forgotten, but I will pass it along =)</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
You're right...it wasn't forgotten.  It was outright rejected.  Here is the exact quote from the Top 10 List:<br />
<a href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=rangerbalance&amp;message.id=3800" target="_blank">http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq...message.id=3800</a><br />
<i>8 -- Improve Harmony (There arent any plans to make changes to Harmony)</i><br />
<br />
This is unacceptable.  Flat-Out unacceptable.  By giving other classes lull/pacify/harmony upgrades and not giving us one, you ARE taking this utility away from us.  It's not a matter of spreading it around.  If you wanted to spread it around, you would have given us ALL an upgrade.  By allowing others to exceed our own abilities in this arena and not giving us the ability to match them, you are TAKING IT AWAY FROM US.<br />
<br />
We need it back.  Now.<br />
<br />
Whew!  That was a long post.  It took over 4 hours to write (and two more hours to edit the next morning!)  Sorry about that, but you said a lot that I needed to respond to.  Again, I would ask you to please respond, even if it's only enough to let me know my message was received and read.  Thank you.</div>
